1
00:00:01.052 --> 00:00:03.895
Do you think Python was going to get popular from the beginning?

2
00:00:14.849 --> 00:00:21.068
Python has contributed to making critical thinking a little more approachable by more people.

3
00:00:21.396 --> 00:00:25.379
You can spend one to two hours learning programming fundamentals,

4
00:00:25.739 --> 00:00:29.457
and then you can write like 10 to 20 lines of code that do something interesting.

5
00:00:29.647 --> 00:00:30.288
The language,

6
00:00:30.388 --> 00:00:31.047
the community,

7
00:00:31.208 --> 00:00:32.368
the ecosystem,

8
00:00:32.468 --> 00:00:33.088
the market,

9
00:00:33.448 --> 00:00:37.091
the whole thing has had such an impact on humanity.

10
00:00:37.469 --> 00:00:37.692
Today,

11
00:00:37.747 --> 00:00:40.512
I think it's safe to say that almost anywhere there's a computer,

12
00:00:40.591 --> 00:00:41.872
there's probably some Python.

13
00:00:42.348 --> 00:00:44.247
It's literally on Mars.

14
00:00:45.387 --> 00:00:46.505
The impact of AI,

15
00:00:46.646 --> 00:00:48.990
I think we're still seeing what that's going to be.

16
00:00:49.490 --> 00:00:51.240
Python is incredibly important for that.

17
00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:54.786
To fully understand how Python got so big,

18
00:00:55.130 --> 00:00:56.396
we have to go back in time.

19
00:01:00.079 --> 00:01:01.462
Maybe not that far back.

20
00:01:02.862 --> 00:01:04.805
Everything started back in Amsterdam in the

21
00:01:05.185 --> 00:01:07.067
80s, during my time at CWI,

22
00:01:07.368 --> 00:01:08.787
a Dutch research facility.

23
00:01:11.552 --> 00:01:17.521
The CWI had been behind a lot of major programming language developments,

24
00:01:17.771 --> 00:01:19.599
Algos 60 and Algos 68,

25
00:01:19.614 --> 00:01:20.302
for instance.

26
00:01:21.067 --> 00:01:21.364
And

27
00:01:21.724 --> 00:01:28.942
Lombeer-Meertens had tried teaching programming to artists and discovered things about programming.

28
00:01:29.408 --> 00:01:32.251
That are easy if you're a scientist or a geek.

29
00:01:32.450 --> 00:01:34.492
But for somebody like an artist,

30
00:01:34.772 --> 00:01:39.456
those things weren't obvious because you had to know something about the computer.

31
00:01:39.777 --> 00:01:44.284
The cost of the frustration was the low level of languages that were available.

32
00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:47.120
The computers were immensely expensive.

33
00:01:47.385 --> 00:01:48.605
And compared with that,

34
00:01:49.027 --> 00:01:50.323
a programmer was really,

35
00:01:50.402 --> 00:01:50.963
really cheap.

36
00:01:51.823 --> 00:01:57.260
And so programming languages were designed with that economic relationship in mind.

37
00:01:57.683 --> 00:01:58.683
It didn't matter.

38
00:01:59.028 --> 00:02:00.810
If it took a long time to program,

39
00:02:01.349 --> 00:02:04.313
as long as it didn't demand too much of the computer,

40
00:02:04.373 --> 00:02:05.915
because that's where the cost was.

41
00:02:07.016 --> 00:02:08.337
We looked at each other and said,

42
00:02:08.438 --> 00:02:09.478
can't we do a better job?

43
00:02:09.641 --> 00:02:12.181
Can't we design a language that is easy to learn,

44
00:02:12.282 --> 00:02:13.118
easy to teach,

45
00:02:13.259 --> 00:02:15.502
but also easy to use?

46
00:02:15.766 --> 00:02:22.252
So that beginners could understand how to program without having to go into all those messy hardware details.

47
00:02:22.391 --> 00:02:23.313
And that's how the

48
00:02:23.752 --> 00:02:25.096
ABC project was born.

49
00:02:28.063 --> 00:02:31.307
One of the members of that team was Guido van Rossum.

50
00:02:39.795 --> 00:02:42.359
I was hired to work on ABC,

51
00:02:42.975 --> 00:02:45.038
for which there was a small prototype,

52
00:02:45.835 --> 00:02:51.007
but every part of the prototype had to be expanded to fully working according to the spec.

53
00:02:54.207 --> 00:02:56.069
In 1985,

54
00:02:56.070 --> 00:02:57.890
we made the release of ABC.

55
00:02:59.212 --> 00:03:00.573
And then we hit the problem,

56
00:03:01.155 --> 00:03:04.474
how to make the world know that there was ABC.

57
00:03:05.358 --> 00:03:10.811
We did not have a good way of reaching our intended audience.

58
00:03:11.139 --> 00:03:12.701
The internet did not exist.

59
00:03:13.045 --> 00:03:17.264
Most people had never heard of a computer or even seen one.

60
00:03:17.748 --> 00:03:18.998
If anybody wanted a copy,

61
00:03:19.451 --> 00:03:20.592
they had to send us a letter,

62
00:03:21.233 --> 00:03:22.780
and we'd send them a floppy disk.

63
00:03:24.376 --> 00:03:27.800
So I'm afraid ABC reached very few people.

64
00:03:28.159 --> 00:03:29.100
And at some point,

65
00:03:29.102 --> 00:03:29.819
the directors,

66
00:03:29.920 --> 00:03:31.984
for a reason that I still don't understand,

67
00:03:32.284 --> 00:03:33.543
killed that project.

68
00:03:34.104 --> 00:03:34.847
I had spent,

69
00:03:35.550 --> 00:03:35.769
well,

70
00:03:35.871 --> 00:03:44.300
three and a half years of hard work on this language and the implementation to make it as good as we could.

71
00:03:44.597 --> 00:03:45.737
So it was disappointing.

72
00:03:45.753 --> 00:03:52.081
Guido was transferred to another project.

73
00:03:52.644 --> 00:03:54.925
On a distributed operating system,

74
00:03:55.407 --> 00:03:56.588
the AmoeBa system.

75
00:03:59.189 --> 00:04:02.233
One of my jobs at that project as the programmer,

76
00:04:02.295 --> 00:04:03.193
not the researcher,

77
00:04:03.451 --> 00:04:09.552
was to write or help write a large number of user applications.

78
00:04:10.224 --> 00:04:14.177
And I didn't actually think that for many of those utilities,

79
00:04:15.021 --> 00:04:16.725
C was a very good language.

80
00:04:18.552 --> 00:04:19.225
And I thought,

81
00:04:19.350 --> 00:04:19.694
well,

82
00:04:19.896 --> 00:04:20.630
oh man,

83
00:04:20.694 --> 00:04:21.413
if we just could...

84
00:04:21.776 --> 00:04:24.317
Program ABC instead of C.

85
00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:27.983
Each of those utilities would be like half a page of code,

86
00:04:28.103 --> 00:04:31.584
and I could write the entire suite of utilities in a couple of weeks,

87
00:04:32.247 --> 00:04:35.326
instead of the years that it looked like it was going to take us.

88
00:04:36.192 --> 00:04:36.951
Except that

89
00:04:37.591 --> 00:04:40.850
ABC was so high and abstract,

90
00:04:40.959 --> 00:04:51.350
it wasn't a good language to talk to. Servers and file systems and processes, and it's sort of the whole operating system thing.

91
00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:54.043
Was abstracted away from ABC.

92
00:04:54.584 --> 00:04:55.283
So I thought,

93
00:04:55.343 --> 00:04:55.504
well,

94
00:04:55.523 --> 00:05:00.408
there really ought to be a language that sort of bridges the gap between C and shell.

95
00:05:01.088 --> 00:05:02.329
And we looked at Perl,

96
00:05:02.509 --> 00:05:07.298
and we didn't think it was any good as a programming language.

97
00:05:08.721 --> 00:05:11.110
It was about as bad as basic,

98
00:05:11.173 --> 00:05:12.346
although in different ways.

99
00:05:12.735 --> 00:05:17.829
So Python was also in a part built as an alternative to Perl.

100
00:05:18.704 --> 00:05:19.721
That's where I decided,

101
00:05:19.908 --> 00:05:20.033
oh,

102
00:05:20.110 --> 00:05:20.314
well.

103
00:05:20.939 --> 00:05:23.903
I'm going to see if I can make my own programming language.

104
00:05:28.809 --> 00:05:30.048
One Christmas holiday,

105
00:05:30.110 --> 00:05:30.548
I believe,

106
00:05:30.726 --> 00:05:37.218
He decided to spend his time designing and building a new programming language for the operating system,

107
00:05:37.735 --> 00:05:41.016
based on the principles that he'd learned while on the ABC project.

108
00:05:42.016 --> 00:05:44.750
It was logical that I would start with ABC as

109
00:05:45.201 --> 00:05:45.980
as an example.

110
00:05:46.221 --> 00:05:55.262
The most prominent feature that Python borrowed from ABC is actually the use of indentation for statement grouping.

111
00:05:55.583 --> 00:06:01.848
But it was also logical that I sort of dropped the things from ABC that I didn't particularly like.

112
00:06:02.052 --> 00:06:03.223
That's how we ended up with

113
00:06:03.692 --> 00:06:04.129
Python.

114
00:06:10.286 --> 00:06:11.348
Okay.

115
00:06:13.812 --> 00:06:17.115
I finally was confident enough of the interpreter,

116
00:06:17.216 --> 00:06:18.478
was complete enough that

117
00:06:18.939 --> 00:06:20.617
I showed it to Lambert.

118
00:06:20.619 --> 00:06:24.586
He showed me a language he had developed stealthily,

119
00:06:24.946 --> 00:06:26.048
which he calls Python,

120
00:06:26.384 --> 00:06:27.649
named after Monty Python.

121
00:06:28.704 --> 00:06:29.048
I said,

122
00:06:29.125 --> 00:06:29.923
look what I made.

123
00:06:30.750 --> 00:06:34.266
It was clear to me that it had some resemblance to ABC.

124
00:06:34.798 --> 00:06:36.750
The command line prompt is even the same.

125
00:06:37.516 --> 00:06:37.641
So

126
00:06:38.064 --> 00:06:41.000
Lambert watched me type a few things and...

127
00:06:41.002 --> 00:06:41.579
And he was.

128
00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:46.324
Excited about it, and he apparently thought I would be excited as well.

129
00:06:46.547 --> 00:06:48.309
At some point he had seen enough and he said,

130
00:06:48.327 --> 00:06:49.367
Can I try something?

131
00:06:49.730 --> 00:06:54.153
And he types one very short line of code and it crashes the interpreter.

132
00:06:57.112 --> 00:06:58.894
And he knew that it would.

133
00:06:59.723 --> 00:07:00.644
The point escaped me.

134
00:07:00.675 --> 00:07:07.362
I didn't know why he thought this was better than ABC and why he had done this whole project.

135
00:07:07.581 --> 00:07:10.004
I went back and the next day I had a fix for it.

136
00:07:11.632 --> 00:07:13.654
It was a pretty crushing experience,

137
00:07:13.656 --> 00:07:14.396
to be honest.

138
00:07:28.654 --> 00:07:33.170
It must have been at least half a year later that I first got acquainted with Python.

139
00:07:33.858 --> 00:07:35.451
So this is the office where

140
00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:39.701
Guido and I were holed up when he created Python.

141
00:07:40.257 --> 00:07:42.059
There were two important users.

142
00:07:42.139 --> 00:07:44.863
Sjoerd was one of them, and the other was Jack Janssen.

143
00:07:47.485 --> 00:07:51.488
Guido was sitting over there and I was sitting over there.

144
00:07:52.309 --> 00:07:54.269
If you want to prototype a program,

145
00:07:54.831 --> 00:07:58.903
you sort of write the outlines of the program,

146
00:07:59.168 --> 00:08:00.403
but it doesn't actually work.

147
00:08:00.793 --> 00:08:01.870
When you do this in Python,

148
00:08:02.184 --> 00:08:02.995
it actually works.

149
00:08:03.355 --> 00:08:04.105
It's readable,

150
00:08:04.793 --> 00:08:06.245
it's very easy to program,

151
00:08:06.887 --> 00:08:09.089
and the indentation is totally natural.

152
00:08:09.617 --> 00:08:10.898
As far as I'm concerned, anyway.

153
00:08:11.399 --> 00:08:14.882
Sjoerd and Jack were the most active in using Python.

154
00:08:15.221 --> 00:08:15.904
You find bugs,

155
00:08:16.002 --> 00:08:18.201
you find the things that you want to extend.

156
00:08:18.389 --> 00:08:19.624
And then telling me about it,

157
00:08:19.725 --> 00:08:21.468
because all they had to do was say,

158
00:08:21.569 --> 00:08:22.093
Hey, Guido.

159
00:08:23.249 --> 00:08:27.858
It was the first real interactive systems programming language,

160
00:08:27.874 --> 00:08:31.560
so you could just sit and write and run it immediately, without any compilation.

161
00:08:31.764 --> 00:08:35.249
So it was much more fun to use than the old programming languages,

162
00:08:35.576 --> 00:08:36.107
but slower.

163
00:08:39.157 --> 00:08:41.980
I think it was mostly Jack's idea in the end,

164
00:08:42.059 --> 00:08:43.240
while we all worked on it,

165
00:08:43.559 --> 00:08:45.224
to make an open source release.

166
00:08:45.763 --> 00:08:47.345
CWI allowed

167
00:08:47.688 --> 00:08:52.447
Guido to distribute Python to the world as long as this copyright notice was there.

168
00:08:53.134 --> 00:08:57.813
They would have held back if they had known it would be such an incredible success.

169
00:08:58.298 --> 00:08:59.783
Which is good that they didn't know.

170
00:08:59.923 --> 00:09:00.438
Nobody knew.

171
00:09:00.595 --> 00:09:01.595
I didn't either.

172
00:09:01.953 --> 00:09:03.658
Because if they had held back,

173
00:09:03.703 --> 00:09:06.078
it would never have become an incredible success.

174
00:09:08.876 --> 00:09:11.698
Then we had to actually physically do the release,

175
00:09:11.780 --> 00:09:13.980
which turned out to be an incredible pain,

176
00:09:14.043 --> 00:09:17.488
because Usenet was the only thing we had to release it.

177
00:09:22.831 --> 00:09:25.385
UseNet was a network of,

178
00:09:26.027 --> 00:09:26.480
you could say,

179
00:09:26.573 --> 00:09:27.418
bulletin boards.

180
00:09:28.293 --> 00:09:29.635
People would write messages,

181
00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:31.980
they would get distributed over the world,

182
00:09:32.152 --> 00:09:36.182
and then there were the groups for all the different computer languages.

183
00:09:38.557 --> 00:09:42.462
Usenit had a very strict limit on the size of a single post.

184
00:09:43.041 --> 00:09:43.399
First,

185
00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:46.346
put your entire source tree in a tarball.

186
00:09:47.688 --> 00:09:48.649
Then compress it.

187
00:09:49.330 --> 00:09:53.009
Then you have to do another step where you turn the binary data into

188
00:09:53.494 --> 00:09:54.626
ASCII encoding.

189
00:09:55.673 --> 00:09:59.235
So you have this huge file with gobbledygook,

190
00:09:59.330 --> 00:10:02.126
but it's at least printable gobbledygook.

191
00:10:02.846 --> 00:10:05.705
Then you apply another tool that snips it into pieces.

192
00:10:07.476 --> 00:10:11.981
Then there is a script where if you have downloaded all 21 parts,

193
00:10:12.384 --> 00:10:15.164
you can undo all those operations in reverse.

194
00:10:16.086 --> 00:10:17.625
That was what people put up with.

195
00:10:17.743 --> 00:10:28.259
So we did all the work on our side and plenty of people did all the work on their side to unpack this. Because I had apparently written a very good teaser of what this was.

196
00:10:35.980 --> 00:10:36.721
Very quickly,

197
00:10:37.041 --> 00:10:46.147
I started getting feedback via email or Usenax from people who had done something exciting with it, or who had found a bug.

198
00:10:46.623 --> 00:10:47.764
And that just kept coming.

199
00:10:51.107 --> 00:10:52.505
We worked at Johnson Space Center.

200
00:10:52.850 --> 00:11:02.005
So our interest was putting together flight simulations and tools for the design engineers that would be used for a shuttle program at the time.

201
00:11:04.793 --> 00:11:13.041
I remember needing a scripting language to control a C++ library project we were working on at the time.

202
00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:16.423
Not too long into that search,

203
00:11:16.884 --> 00:11:20.048
I found Guidos Python Distribution at CWI.

204
00:11:20.572 --> 00:11:22.274
I was able to FTP that down,

205
00:11:25.572 --> 00:11:26.057
unpack it,

206
00:11:27.087 --> 00:11:27.587
compile it,

207
00:11:28.916 --> 00:11:31.384
and run it in a matter of 10 minutes or so.

208
00:11:32.836 --> 00:11:36.823
That was my first impressive experience with Python.

209
00:11:37.385 --> 00:11:38.148
Twenty years ago,

210
00:11:38.586 --> 00:11:45.879
a computer that cost a million dollars and filled an entire room had less capability than an 11-pound desktop computer today.

211
00:11:46.859 --> 00:11:49.461
With costs going down and capabilities going up,

212
00:11:49.981 --> 00:11:52.845
the computer has entered our lives quickly and unobtrusively.

213
00:11:53.243 --> 00:11:59.774
There were lots of things changing in a major way that made computing particularly exciting to be in at that time.

214
00:12:00.009 --> 00:12:04.461
Computers suddenly were coming out of the machine room and landing up on your desk,

215
00:12:04.711 --> 00:12:04.961
and then,

216
00:12:04.977 --> 00:12:05.259
of course,

217
00:12:05.259 --> 00:12:05.993
the web happened,

218
00:12:06.134 --> 00:12:07.211
then it all exploded.

219
00:12:08.086 --> 00:12:10.539
After the internet came to Europe,

220
00:12:10.618 --> 00:12:13.461
it was much easier for software to be distributed.

221
00:12:13.868 --> 00:12:15.822
Python very slowly...

222
00:12:16.407 --> 00:12:16.807
Took off.

223
00:12:17.548 --> 00:12:21.451
Then there was a growing Python community, which was very supportive,

224
00:12:22.150 --> 00:12:24.154
like a big family, you could almost say.

225
00:12:30.357 --> 00:12:32.100
Part of the benefit of this is that

226
00:12:33.279 --> 00:12:33.639
I don't,

227
00:12:34.264 --> 00:12:36.514
I'm like, there's no strain on my body at all.

228
00:12:37.654 --> 00:12:45.749
I was working on developing a kind of distributed equipment database, and a colleague at the lab,

229
00:12:46.010 --> 00:12:52.616
Michael McClay, knew that. I was looking for what was called a scripting language that was also sophisticated,

230
00:12:52.777 --> 00:12:57.866
that would enable you to build substantial things and not get bogged down in the ragged edges.

231
00:12:58.163 --> 00:13:03.070
Scripting languages were designed to glue things together,

232
00:13:03.100 --> 00:13:04.881
to connect things that already worked,

233
00:13:04.913 --> 00:13:06.053
that already existed.

234
00:13:06.445 --> 00:13:07.710
Immediately on trying it,

235
00:13:07.756 --> 00:13:09.960
I was just amazed and thought,

236
00:13:10.053 --> 00:13:11.663
this can't be as good as it is.

237
00:13:12.023 --> 00:13:12.475
And it was.

238
00:13:14.115 --> 00:13:17.558
Mike was interested in bringing Guido over,

239
00:13:18.097 --> 00:13:20.140
and Guido was interested in coming over.

240
00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:21.621
99%

241
00:13:21.660 --> 00:13:25.706
of the people that I got in touch with were in the United States.

242
00:13:26.386 --> 00:13:26.504
So

243
00:13:27.105 --> 00:13:28.028
Guido ended up coming.

244
00:13:28.785 --> 00:13:30.192
And then Mike and

245
00:13:30.535 --> 00:13:39.614
Guido and I wanted to arrange a workshop so people who were interested in Python could gather and talk about what they were working on and what they felt was needed.

246
00:13:41.176 --> 00:13:43.004
This is the t-shirt for the first.

247
00:13:43.174 --> 00:13:43.855
conference.

248
00:13:43.856 --> 00:13:44.436
And so this,

249
00:13:46.017 --> 00:13:46.278
yeah,

250
00:13:46.719 --> 00:13:48.541
that was just sort of flowy writing.

251
00:13:48.599 --> 00:13:49.763
And on the back,

252
00:13:51.287 --> 00:13:54.287
it gave the date of the conference.

253
00:13:54.748 --> 00:13:55.005
Spum,

254
00:13:55.130 --> 00:13:55.403
spum,

255
00:13:55.528 --> 00:13:55.809
spum,

256
00:13:55.927 --> 00:13:56.248
spum.

257
00:13:56.990 --> 00:13:58.309
It's such a fantastic song.

258
00:13:59.395 --> 00:14:01.130
That workshop really is,

259
00:14:01.177 --> 00:14:01.427
for me,

260
00:14:01.599 --> 00:14:03.255
the beginning of the Python community,

261
00:14:03.333 --> 00:14:04.817
November 1994,

262
00:14:05.240 --> 00:14:05.958
Gaithersburg,

263
00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:06.583
Maryland,

264
00:14:06.630 --> 00:14:09.755
in this windowless government office building at NIST.

265
00:14:10.287 --> 00:14:11.349
That was a great experience.

266
00:14:11.442 --> 00:14:12.349
That was about two days.

267
00:14:13.071 --> 00:14:13.892
We had 20 people.

268
00:14:14.652 --> 00:14:17.073
I still have the t-shirt from that workshop.

269
00:14:17.394 --> 00:14:19.557
There was just kind of this feel of,

270
00:14:19.635 --> 00:14:19.777
hey,

271
00:14:19.859 --> 00:14:20.918
there's something happening.

272
00:14:20.961 --> 00:14:25.484
This will be fun to hang out with the people that I chat with online.

273
00:14:25.702 --> 00:14:28.547
Actually see Guido in person and actually make decisions.

274
00:14:28.548 --> 00:14:33.155
And we knew that if you impressed him with the feature and it was an easy thing to install,

275
00:14:33.187 --> 00:14:37.092
he would add it to the language right there. So that we can at least try it out in beta form.

276
00:14:37.312 --> 00:14:40.234
It was like a whole room of people who knew what you were talking about.

277
00:14:40.506 --> 00:14:42.849
Because they had all studied Python deeply,

278
00:14:43.370 --> 00:14:44.129
or almost all.

279
00:14:45.532 --> 00:14:47.231
One of the people was Barry Warsaw.

280
00:14:47.232 --> 00:14:57.349
Around 1994,

281
00:14:57.427 --> 00:14:58.270
I joined a company,

282
00:14:58.427 --> 00:14:59.145
CNRI,

283
00:14:59.379 --> 00:15:01.427
Corporation for National Research Initiatives.

284
00:15:02.004 --> 00:15:05.254
And we were building these software agents,

285
00:15:05.552 --> 00:15:07.474
little programs that can move around.

286
00:15:07.658 --> 00:15:14.318
To different computers on a network. And they pickle themselves up and move around to another place and reconstitute themselves and do some more work.

287
00:15:14.799 --> 00:15:16.260
A friend of mine from

288
00:15:16.721 --> 00:15:19.143
NIST sent me an email and said,

289
00:15:19.158 --> 00:15:19.283
hey,

290
00:15:19.339 --> 00:15:23.260
we've got this guy coming over from the Netherlands and he's going to talk about his language.

291
00:15:23.283 --> 00:15:24.096
Do you want to come?

292
00:15:24.268 --> 00:15:32.378
And so we went to the workshop and just absolutely fell in love with, of course, Python and of course, Guido.

293
00:15:32.783 --> 00:15:33.628
Even then,

294
00:15:34.018 --> 00:15:36.658
it had the feeling that there was a there there.

295
00:15:37.270 --> 00:15:39.734
That there was something that was going to happen,

296
00:15:39.773 --> 00:15:40.995
that there was potential.

297
00:15:41.214 --> 00:15:43.437
I remember coming back to CNRI and saying,

298
00:15:43.519 --> 00:15:44.135
Oh, this is great,

299
00:15:44.159 --> 00:15:46.698
we're going to use Python, for sure, in our project.

300
00:15:46.980 --> 00:15:50.323
And one of our colleagues at CNRI said,

301
00:15:50.924 --> 00:15:51.629
Well, what do you think,

302
00:15:51.721 --> 00:15:53.581
why don't we just hire Guido?

303
00:16:04.644 --> 00:16:06.721
CNRI was set up to sort of promote

304
00:16:07.154 --> 00:16:08.514
information infrastructure,

305
00:16:08.634 --> 00:16:09.635
foster research,

306
00:16:10.535 --> 00:16:12.076
help build pilot projects,

307
00:16:12.596 --> 00:16:13.534
take the results,

308
00:16:14.057 --> 00:16:17.780
and put them out into the public so that others could then leverage it.

309
00:16:18.014 --> 00:16:21.562
Part of CNRI's mission was to cultivate internet-based things.

310
00:16:21.835 --> 00:16:23.405
That's why our name,

311
00:16:23.812 --> 00:16:26.280
Corporation for National Research Initiatives,

312
00:16:26.764 --> 00:16:28.451
had four initiatives in there.

313
00:16:32.826 --> 00:16:36.437
We had a need for a language that

314
00:16:36.863 --> 00:16:43.239
would be easier for people to deal with than any other traditional languages that were around at the time.

315
00:16:43.621 --> 00:16:45.039
I ran across a photograph.

316
00:16:45.101 --> 00:16:46.407
There was a party at sea.

317
00:16:46.962 --> 00:16:47.403
.Year. ago.

318
00:16:47.924 --> 00:16:48.664
It was probably,

319
00:16:48.725 --> 00:16:49.046
I think,

320
00:16:49.446 --> 00:16:52.690
1996.

321
00:16:52.710 --> 00:16:55.049
And it's a Guido Ramos.

322
00:16:56.033 --> 00:16:56.150
Yeah,

323
00:16:56.152 --> 00:16:56.956
I used to say Guido.

324
00:16:57.214 --> 00:16:58.236
Many people say Guido,

325
00:16:58.315 --> 00:16:59.072
but I said Guido.

326
00:16:59.456 --> 00:17:02.480
And I'm sure I don't pronounce it right.

327
00:17:02.480 --> 00:17:02.596
Oh,

328
00:17:02.597 --> 00:17:04.144
he was a very stylish person.

329
00:17:04.299 --> 00:17:05.799
He was a very strong fellow.

330
00:17:05.940 --> 00:17:07.096
I got introduced to him,

331
00:17:07.346 --> 00:17:08.987
and it just seemed like it was a good fit.

332
00:17:09.065 --> 00:17:10.580
And so I made the job offer.

333
00:17:10.769 --> 00:17:11.049
For me,

334
00:17:11.080 --> 00:17:12.424
it was fantastic.

335
00:17:13.221 --> 00:17:14.690
There's no doubt about that.

336
00:17:14.971 --> 00:17:15.315
One of the

337
00:17:15.398 --> 00:17:16.601
things he insists on,

338
00:17:16.901 --> 00:17:18.320
if you want to get him to work for you,

339
00:17:18.421 --> 00:17:20.385
is that he has some fraction of his time,

340
00:17:21.463 --> 00:17:23.346
preferably as much as half time,

341
00:17:23.347 --> 00:17:23.963
if not more,

342
00:17:24.424 --> 00:17:25.791
to work on the language itself.

343
00:17:26.010 --> 00:17:28.494
The fact that they could work full-time on Python,

344
00:17:29.471 --> 00:17:35.651
because it turned out that the Nobots project was almost more an excuse to hire me than

345
00:17:35.994 --> 00:17:37.198
I did. Much for that.

346
00:17:38.119 --> 00:17:42.151
I kind of feel like our work on Python was a little subversive.

347
00:17:42.385 --> 00:17:42.666
You know,

348
00:17:42.682 --> 00:17:42.807
we...

349
00:17:43.222 --> 00:17:46.625
Tended to spend a lot more time on Python than maybe we should have.

350
00:17:46.987 --> 00:17:50.229
I went to CNRI and since I had been a systems person,

351
00:17:50.749 --> 00:17:53.593
I was responsible for setting up python.org.

352
00:17:54.154 --> 00:18:04.226
We should have also grabbed Python.com, even though we didn't think of Python as a commercial enterprise. Because someone else got it and used it to host this stupid porn site.

353
00:18:04.601 --> 00:18:05.226
For years,

354
00:18:05.257 --> 00:18:06.585
we had to warn people,

355
00:18:06.804 --> 00:18:08.007
go to python.org,

356
00:18:08.101 --> 00:18:08.788
not .com.

357
00:18:13.770 --> 00:18:15.432
It really was the perfect home,

358
00:18:15.653 --> 00:18:15.992
I think,

359
00:18:16.073 --> 00:18:21.460
for doing all of that early Python development and develop a lot of the infrastructure around Python.

360
00:18:21.619 --> 00:18:29.874
We had a meeting discussing making some kind of user group or software organization where the Python software activity was proposed.

361
00:18:30.124 --> 00:18:31.343
We need a little bit of governance,

362
00:18:31.654 --> 00:18:33.249
a little bit of organization,

363
00:18:33.529 --> 00:18:37.108
but we don't want too much because I don't think any of us really like bureaucracy.

364
00:18:37.779 --> 00:18:41.671
And then the question came up about what we should call Guido as part of that.

365
00:18:41.874 --> 00:18:42.654
I think it was.

366
00:18:43.346 --> 00:18:43.467
Me,

367
00:18:43.686 --> 00:18:44.688
who suggested that

368
00:18:45.670 --> 00:18:47.633
Guido be called a benevolent dictator.

369
00:18:48.292 --> 00:18:51.292
And then Barry suggested benevolent dictator for life.

370
00:18:52.636 --> 00:18:54.855
And that became an internet meme,

371
00:18:54.917 --> 00:18:57.160
or actually a software meme.

372
00:18:57.441 --> 00:18:58.785
Benevolent dictator for life.

373
00:19:00.207 --> 00:19:01.785
You can find it on Wikipedia.

374
00:19:04.191 --> 00:19:04.753
Ultimately,

375
00:19:05.410 --> 00:19:05.644
you know,

376
00:19:05.722 --> 00:19:08.847
Guido was the inventor of the language and...

377
00:19:09.078 --> 00:19:10.539
The final decider about,

378
00:19:10.601 --> 00:19:10.780
yes,

379
00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:13.163
this is going to make it in, or this is not going to make it in?

380
00:19:13.324 --> 00:19:18.527
I think I developed my own style during those first years.

381
00:19:19.410 --> 00:19:21.074
All ideas are welcome,

382
00:19:21.574 --> 00:19:26.863
but I will choose which ideas I believe are right to add to the language.

383
00:19:27.644 --> 00:19:37.941
There's dozens and dozens of aspects of Python today where somebody had a vision for, if you just

384
00:19:38.262 --> 00:19:39.523
add this to Python,

385
00:19:40.125 --> 00:19:48.856
Look at all these amazing things that I can do.

386
00:19:48.857 --> 00:19:50.678
I'm one of the many people that came to Python,

387
00:19:50.692 --> 00:19:51.513
not as a programmer,

388
00:19:51.553 --> 00:19:52.513
but as a scientist.

389
00:19:52.756 --> 00:19:54.873
Python wasn't the first language I used for science.

390
00:19:55.045 --> 00:19:57.045
I was doing satellite data processing,

391
00:19:57.576 --> 00:19:58.685
and I used Perl to do it.

392
00:19:58.810 --> 00:19:59.670
And then, a year later,

393
00:19:59.685 --> 00:20:01.420
I would come back and try to figure out what I'd done,

394
00:20:01.421 --> 00:20:02.185
and I had no idea.

395
00:20:03.060 --> 00:20:04.717
Python had the opposite experience.

396
00:20:04.748 --> 00:20:06.653
I first started using Python in 1997.

397
00:20:07.191 --> 00:20:08.971
I just used it to do some scripting,

398
00:20:08.972 --> 00:20:11.236
do some data processing with some medical imaging data.

399
00:20:11.736 --> 00:20:12.095
And I was like,

400
00:20:12.096 --> 00:20:12.196
hey,

401
00:20:12.198 --> 00:20:12.736
this is nice.

402
00:20:12.737 --> 00:20:13.715
This is pretty cool.

403
00:20:13.959 --> 00:20:14.657
A year later,

404
00:20:14.659 --> 00:20:15.782
so 1998,

405
00:20:16.056 --> 00:20:18.939
I came back to look at the code I'd written and I could read it.

406
00:20:19.025 --> 00:20:20.001
I understood what I did.

407
00:20:20.603 --> 00:20:21.548
And that was kind of,

408
00:20:21.548 --> 00:20:21.782
for me,

409
00:20:21.806 --> 00:20:23.142
the convincing data that said,

410
00:20:23.220 --> 00:20:23.345
oh,

411
00:20:23.392 --> 00:20:24.704
I need to dig in on this language.

412
00:20:26.470 --> 00:20:32.048
And there were a few really key people at that time who were publishing or talking about how to use Python for science.

413
00:20:32.079 --> 00:20:32.611
Not very many,

414
00:20:32.689 --> 00:20:33.079
but a few.

415
00:20:33.564 --> 00:20:35.173
Conrad Hinson was one of them.

416
00:20:35.204 --> 00:20:35.579
I remember,

417
00:20:35.673 --> 00:20:36.798
and David Asher and...

418
00:20:37.406 --> 00:20:37.547
Jim,

419
00:20:37.626 --> 00:20:38.147
you're going to add?

420
00:20:38.788 --> 00:20:52.540
There's been a number of stages in the lifecycle of Python when it just grew from a core language capability to a platform with a number of different specialty modules and packages. That made it very,

421
00:20:52.604 --> 00:20:55.611
very useful for certain user communities.

422
00:20:56.268 --> 00:20:58.893
The first one was probably the numeric community,

423
00:20:59.221 --> 00:21:03.611
the science and engineering folks that wanted high-performance matrix operations to be done.

424
00:21:04.530 --> 00:21:06.453
Even though Guido wasn't a scientist himself,

425
00:21:06.534 --> 00:21:11.078
wasn't necessarily deeply concerned with the same things that we were concerned with as scientists,

426
00:21:11.477 --> 00:21:13.680
he was open to the suggestions.

427
00:21:16.563 --> 00:21:31.031
I think one of the things that people don't appreciate about the Python language as much now that it's so popular and mainstream, is how important it was. That Guido was open to new ideas and open to the needs of people who are not traditional programmers.

428
00:21:32.810 --> 00:21:35.074
I think he had a very clear-eyed,

429
00:21:35.613 --> 00:21:42.741
quiet focus on understanding some things about the future that he built into the language.

430
00:21:42.819 --> 00:21:45.461
It was uniquely suited to its environment.

431
00:21:45.780 --> 00:21:46.405
One of the reasons...

432
00:21:46.510 --> 00:21:47.172
I used Python.

433
00:21:47.173 --> 00:21:48.912
And I think a lot of people used Python at the time.

434
00:21:48.993 --> 00:21:49.253
Instead,

435
00:21:49.273 --> 00:21:50.234
in the early 2000s,

436
00:21:50.795 --> 00:21:52.498
the world was almost divided into,

437
00:21:52.979 --> 00:21:54.159
here's an open source ecosystem,

438
00:21:54.440 --> 00:21:55.759
or you can go and use Java,

439
00:21:55.962 --> 00:21:57.823
which is actually a paid thing.

440
00:21:58.159 --> 00:21:59.221
I was using MATLAB.

441
00:21:59.462 --> 00:22:02.893
I really didn't like the fact that when I wrote code and I wanted to share that code with others,

442
00:22:02.923 --> 00:22:09.159
I was essentially telling people. They had to go buy a license for a software package before they could even look at my code or use my code.

443
00:22:09.160 --> 00:22:09.487
You know,

444
00:22:09.488 --> 00:22:14.721
these are the days where you have to buy the developer tools or spend a couple hundred bucks to get.

445
00:22:14.906 --> 00:22:22.229
Visual Studio 6.0. And then Python, and then all of these libraries were open source and then could be used in a commercial project.

446
00:22:22.388 --> 00:22:37.685
I was sort of early on convinced by community members that Python being open source and the particular way it was open source was very important. So that people would feel comfortable using Python to make great

447
00:22:37.826 --> 00:22:40.499
things that they would then be able to sell.

448
00:22:52.412 --> 00:22:56.037
In 1998, Blender was published on the internet.

449
00:22:56.795 --> 00:22:59.803
The software was free and you could buy some things around it.

450
00:23:00.684 --> 00:23:03.724
We were restricted to use open source,

451
00:23:04.020 --> 00:23:05.990
so you didn't have a lot of options.

452
00:23:06.584 --> 00:23:09.270
We were doing a call on our website like,

453
00:23:09.317 --> 00:23:13.334
what is the most popular scripting language that we should add in Blender?

454
00:23:14.027 --> 00:23:15.568
Perl was really big,

455
00:23:16.348 --> 00:23:18.231
and Python was upcoming,

456
00:23:18.353 --> 00:23:19.250
and there were some others.

457
00:23:19.711 --> 00:23:26.981
And it was interesting to see that everybody who was advising us to use perl as scripting language,

458
00:23:27.419 --> 00:23:31.005
but they only advertised how great perl is.

459
00:23:31.786 --> 00:23:35.661
And the people who came more from the Python background,

460
00:23:36.067 --> 00:23:36.411
who said,

461
00:23:36.442 --> 00:23:36.583
well,

462
00:23:36.630 --> 00:23:38.473
I think Python is the baddest choice,

463
00:23:38.958 --> 00:23:40.880
they came with a balanced opinion.

464
00:23:40.895 --> 00:23:41.286
And they said,

465
00:23:41.348 --> 00:23:41.551
okay.

466
00:23:41.767 --> 00:23:45.871
Perl will give you this and this and this, and Python will give you other things.

467
00:23:46.433 --> 00:23:48.094
And balancing all of it,

468
00:23:48.172 --> 00:23:50.394
I would recommend you to do Python.

469
00:23:50.738 --> 00:23:53.675
And only for that reason I picked Python.

470
00:23:54.457 --> 00:23:56.082
Just because the people were nicer.

471
00:24:04.394 --> 00:24:04.785
It was...

472
00:24:05.242 --> 00:24:05.542
Honestly,

473
00:24:05.623 --> 00:24:06.765
just a lot of enthusiasts.

474
00:24:06.984 --> 00:24:09.185
It was a lot of people who just enjoyed the language,

475
00:24:09.507 --> 00:24:11.029
enjoyed the people involved with the language,

476
00:24:11.351 --> 00:24:14.671
And it would just happen to be typically motivating enough for people to want to help out.

477
00:24:15.490 --> 00:24:15.976
Ultimately,

478
00:24:16.054 --> 00:24:18.771
there's a sense of fun that comes across,

479
00:24:18.857 --> 00:24:18.976
and

480
00:24:19.476 --> 00:24:22.085
Guido coded that into the name of the language,

481
00:24:22.413 --> 00:24:23.101
influenced by

482
00:24:23.538 --> 00:24:24.257
Monty Python.

483
00:24:25.257 --> 00:24:27.679
It creates a sense of community to have your little jokes.

484
00:24:30.771 --> 00:24:31.585
Tim Peters is...

485
00:24:32.282 --> 00:24:52.105
Famous early example and blending both like the the aesthetics of Python and humor, Tim Peters was this mythical feature creature in the world of Python. And no one had met him. He was out there in the Ether as a wise one to give us advice on what to do with numerical processing. Steve

486
00:24:52.121 --> 00:24:55.433
Majeski sent me some email telling me about Python.

487
00:24:56.303 --> 00:25:00.669
So I started an email correspondence with Guido about the language and about the design,

488
00:25:00.867 --> 00:25:06.997
And I got some of the pre-release code and played with it and talked to him about design decisions and liked it very much.

489
00:25:07.590 --> 00:25:09.497
Tim Peters was a

490
00:25:09.973 --> 00:25:17.200
Python contributor and community member and mentor to me from very early on.

491
00:25:17.387 --> 00:25:19.137
Tim was a channeler of Guido.

492
00:25:19.262 --> 00:25:22.200
He had a really unique way of saying,

493
00:25:22.481 --> 00:25:23.872
I think Guido's going to like this,

494
00:25:24.012 --> 00:25:25.747
or I don't think Guido's going to like that.

495
00:25:25.942 --> 00:25:27.944
There's a poem called The Zen of Python,

496
00:25:28.184 --> 00:25:30.147
which is a partially humorous,

497
00:25:30.246 --> 00:25:35.128
partially serious poem about the aesthetics of Python.

498
00:25:35.589 --> 00:25:37.292
I'm actually looking at the

499
00:25:37.652 --> 00:25:40.019
UseNet post where

500
00:25:40.894 --> 00:25:43.957
Tim posted his first version of the Zen of Python,

501
00:25:44.721 --> 00:25:46.660
although he called it the Way of Python.

502
00:25:47.878 --> 00:25:53.535
And it was in response to some discussion where people were complaining that...

503
00:25:53.994 --> 00:25:56.797
They didn't understand what was Python's philosophy.

504
00:25:57.617 --> 00:25:58.739
They couldn't figure me out.

505
00:25:58.917 --> 00:26:00.122
And Tim had figured me out,

506
00:26:00.200 --> 00:26:02.183
and he put it basically in poetry.

507
00:26:03.386 --> 00:26:09.230
Here is the Way of Python by Tim Peters from 1999.

508
00:26:09.231 --> 00:26:10.989
Beautiful is better than ugly.

509
00:26:11.675 --> 00:26:11.972
Duh.

510
00:26:12.692 --> 00:26:14.317
Explicit is better than implicit.

511
00:26:14.753 --> 00:26:16.457
Simple is better than complex.

512
00:26:17.003 --> 00:26:18.832
Complex is better than complicated.

513
00:26:19.722 --> 00:26:20.800
I love that distinction.

514
00:26:21.222 --> 00:26:22.847
Flat is better than nested.

515
00:26:23.366 --> 00:26:24.646
Sparse is better than dense.

516
00:26:24.906 --> 00:26:25.886
Readability counts.

517
00:26:26.186 --> 00:26:27.547
I will say it counts for a lot.

518
00:26:28.308 --> 00:26:32.269
Special cases aren't special enough to break the rules.

519
00:26:32.511 --> 00:26:34.511
Although practicality beats purity,

520
00:26:35.027 --> 00:26:38.886
errors should never pass silently unless explicitly silenced.

521
00:26:39.394 --> 00:26:40.785
In the face of ambiguity,

