1044
00:50:53.525 --> 00:50:55.867
Python 3 just is a better language,

1045
00:50:56.827 --> 00:50:59.652
and it is getting better over time.

1046
00:50:59.813 --> 00:51:00.394
Python 2,

1047
00:51:00.492 --> 00:51:01.331
on the other hand,

1048
00:51:01.496 --> 00:51:02.612
is a fine language,

1049
00:51:03.456 --> 00:51:05.777
and it will remain exactly what it is.

1050
00:51:06.175 --> 00:51:06.996
For a long time,

1051
00:51:07.019 --> 00:51:10.628
there was a lot of measurement of how much Python 2 usage is there,

1052
00:51:10.630 --> 00:51:12.067
how much Python 3 usage is there.

1053
00:51:12.300 --> 00:51:14.112
I think it was when Pycon was in Portland,

1054
00:51:14.347 --> 00:51:16.612
was roughly when we started to see like 50-50.

1055
00:51:17.409 --> 00:51:18.956
Once 3.4 came out,

1056
00:51:19.128 --> 00:51:22.253
it actually added some features that were interesting to people.

1057
00:51:22.498 --> 00:51:22.637
oh,

1058
00:51:22.797 --> 00:51:24.039
I want that capability.

1059
00:51:24.699 --> 00:51:25.061
So to me,

1060
00:51:25.221 --> 00:51:27.842
Python 3.4 was really Python 3.0.

1061
00:51:28.784 --> 00:51:30.827
And then 3.5 was an even bigger milestone.

1062
00:51:31.224 --> 00:51:33.927
That was the one that got widespread adoption of Python 3.

1063
00:51:34.873 --> 00:51:36.913
And by the time Python 3.5 came out,

1064
00:51:36.914 --> 00:51:38.827
then it was clear that Python 3 would work.

1065
00:51:39.170 --> 00:51:43.139
And then you started to have companies come out and give talks, like Instagram's talk,

1066
00:51:43.202 --> 00:51:44.420
which I believe was also important.

1067
00:51:44.422 --> 00:51:45.061
It was a big deal.

1068
00:51:48.780 --> 00:51:48.983
Yes,

1069
00:51:49.061 --> 00:51:49.827
you heard it, right.

1070
00:51:50.186 --> 00:51:51.545
Instagram has been running...

1071
00:51:51.989 --> 00:51:54.010
Fully on Python 3 for a few months.

1072
00:51:55.092 --> 00:51:56.034
The whole process took,

1073
00:51:56.112 --> 00:51:56.514
I would say,

1074
00:51:56.554 --> 00:51:57.956
about 9 to 10 months.

1075
00:51:58.135 --> 00:52:02.983
And I think Instagram is the largest production deployment for Python at the time.

1076
00:52:03.382 --> 00:52:04.639
She gave a very good,

1077
00:52:04.820 --> 00:52:07.905
very thorough talk, explaining why they did it.

1078
00:52:08.061 --> 00:52:08.623
Two main things,

1079
00:52:08.686 --> 00:52:09.967
typing and async IO.

1080
00:52:10.311 --> 00:52:11.092
How they did it.

1081
00:52:11.327 --> 00:52:15.498
We cleaned out all the libraries that are not making the migration from Python 2 to 3.

1082
00:52:15.655 --> 00:52:16.686
How you should do it.

1083
00:52:16.967 --> 00:52:17.514
Unitest.

1084
00:52:17.858 --> 00:52:19.858
What they had learned during the process.

1085
00:52:20.054 --> 00:52:24.157
We had actually some good performance gains as well after our migration.

1086
00:52:24.400 --> 00:52:37.271
It felt as vindication that at least there were large companies that took the time to do it right and to convert all their code to PIFO3 and were able to do it successfully.

1087
00:52:37.896 --> 00:52:39.458
It was definitely well received.

1088
00:52:39.693 --> 00:52:42.911
We got a lot of people saying we really wanted to migrate as well,

1089
00:52:43.474 --> 00:52:48.427
but we weren't getting the kind of support that my team or my company was giving us.

1090
00:52:48.443 --> 00:52:48.755
And now.

1091
00:52:49.057 --> 00:52:51.141
I can bring this back to my management.

1092
00:52:51.201 --> 00:52:54.842
And that really gave people confidence in migrating to Python 3.

1093
00:52:55.923 --> 00:52:57.083
It became like, a,

1094
00:52:57.708 --> 00:52:57.849
look,

1095
00:52:58.123 --> 00:52:59.005
Instagram can do it.

1096
00:52:59.224 --> 00:53:00.130
Why don't you do it?

1097
00:53:00.231 --> 00:53:01.693
Instagram's getting benefits,

1098
00:53:01.833 --> 00:53:02.630
new features,

1099
00:53:02.731 --> 00:53:03.068
faster.

1100
00:53:03.878 --> 00:53:06.358
Why don't you also want that benefit?

1101
00:53:18.202 --> 00:53:20.342
Projects undergo things like this,

1102
00:53:20.577 --> 00:53:20.764
and

1103
00:53:21.561 --> 00:53:22.655
Python learned a lot from it.

1104
00:53:22.842 --> 00:53:26.920
And it did actually eventually end up, with Python 3 being a pretty good spot again,

1105
00:53:27.139 --> 00:53:28.967
that it was safe to use.

1106
00:53:28.969 --> 00:53:30.061
And safe to use. Sounds weird,

1107
00:53:30.077 --> 00:53:30.358
but like...

1108
00:53:30.858 --> 00:53:33.880
Where I felt like I can actually start new projects on Python 3 now,

1109
00:53:34.440 --> 00:53:40.527
because we're back to a stable situation where you're about as productive as I felt like I was with Python 2.

1110
00:53:40.527 --> 00:53:40.590
Hi,

1111
00:53:40.590 --> 00:53:41.409
Anna.

1112
00:53:41.487 --> 00:53:42.690
Nice to meet you.

1113
00:53:42.692 --> 00:53:43.590
I really liked your talk.

1114
00:53:43.768 --> 00:53:45.371
But it was basically time that healed it.

1115
00:53:45.831 --> 00:53:50.534
When Python 2.7 was declared that there wouldn't be any more security fixes,

1116
00:53:50.893 --> 00:53:52.518
it became a security concern.

1117
00:53:52.706 --> 00:53:54.487
That was sort of the final push.

1118
00:53:55.034 --> 00:54:00.143
People who donated their work to do this migration in the wider Python world and community.

1119
00:54:00.557 --> 00:54:02.938
Eventually got the world running on Python 3.

1120
00:54:03.380 --> 00:54:04.041
But, as I said,

1121
00:54:04.081 --> 00:54:05.623
like, it was a decade long process.

1122
00:54:05.724 --> 00:54:09.748
And I don't think anybody anticipated how much work it would need to move to Python 3.

1123
00:54:10.364 --> 00:54:15.436
I think Python's probably too big to ever go through a transition like that today.

1124
00:54:15.592 --> 00:54:19.092
The community was maybe a little too big,

1125
00:54:19.170 --> 00:54:20.356
but not too big.

1126
00:54:20.764 --> 00:54:24.889
I even still get angry messages, sometimes from people who are like,

1127
00:54:25.123 --> 00:54:26.811
my code needs Python 2.7,

1128
00:54:26.856 --> 00:54:27.967
you need to provide it.

1129
00:54:28.106 --> 00:54:29.264
And I tell them, no.

1130
00:54:31.679 --> 00:54:34.623
I never wavered in my commitment to Python 3.

1131
00:54:34.900 --> 00:54:36.724
It was a lesson learned, for sure.

1132
00:54:37.085 --> 00:54:37.885
For a long time,

1133
00:54:37.943 --> 00:54:40.349
I regularly joked there would be a Python 4,

1134
00:54:40.490 --> 00:54:45.771
but the transition would be handled much better than the transition to Python 3.

1135
00:54:45.835 --> 00:54:47.608
I felt I owed that to the community.

1136
00:54:48.342 --> 00:54:52.592
And now the mantra has changed to There will never be even a Python 4.

1137
00:54:53.217 --> 00:54:54.045
To be honest,

1138
00:54:54.389 --> 00:54:58.202
I don't know how many people in Python even know about the whole transition.

1139
00:54:58.693 --> 00:55:01.137
Because that all ended in 2020.

1140
00:55:01.137 --> 00:55:01.956
At least it's behind us.

1141
00:55:18.032 --> 00:55:18.454
Okay,

1142
00:55:18.532 --> 00:55:19.971
so now we get in the closet.

1143
00:55:21.940 --> 00:55:23.423
So there's the Frisbee.

1144
00:55:24.846 --> 00:55:27.657
This is the most unique merch.

1145
00:55:28.065 --> 00:55:30.827
I've ever seen related to Python.

1146
00:55:32.128 --> 00:55:33.769
Now, here's a significant t-shirt.

1147
00:55:34.731 --> 00:55:36.277
It says Python is for girls.

1148
00:55:37.472 --> 00:55:44.081
I received this anonymously in the mail at Google.

1149
00:55:44.722 --> 00:55:45.487
And to this day,

1150
00:55:45.628 --> 00:55:48.737
I don't know exactly what the intention of the sender was.

1151
00:55:48.769 --> 00:55:50.394
They never revealed themselves,

1152
00:55:50.769 --> 00:55:51.534
at least not to me.

1153
00:55:52.567 --> 00:55:54.597
And I don't know if there was an intention even,

1154
00:55:55.269 --> 00:55:57.112
but I sort of realized at that point.

1155
00:55:58.230 --> 00:56:03.195
That there wasn't a whole lot of women in the Python community.

1156
00:56:04.797 --> 00:56:07.699
And the community also discovered that and fixed it for the

1157
00:56:08.059 --> 00:56:09.099
Python conference.

1158
00:56:14.443 --> 00:56:20.349
This idea of being a place where people from a wide range of backgrounds can learn how to program,

1159
00:56:20.474 --> 00:56:21.896
benefit from programming,

1160
00:56:21.989 --> 00:56:22.833
find community.

1161
00:56:23.614 --> 00:56:25.333
There really was some snowballing.

1162
00:56:25.554 --> 00:56:29.056
Adoption of these ideas across languages at the time.

1163
00:56:30.458 --> 00:56:34.501
Jessica McKellar looks at the speakers at Pycon and says,

1164
00:56:34.806 --> 00:56:35.563
there's only 3%

1165
00:56:36.001 --> 00:56:36.563
that are women.

1166
00:56:37.282 --> 00:56:38.282
What can we do about this?

1167
00:56:38.907 --> 00:56:42.572
She was co-organizer of the biggest Python meetup in the world in Boston.

1168
00:56:43.197 --> 00:56:44.431
She knew what she was talking about.

1169
00:56:44.900 --> 00:56:45.916
It's not rocket science.

1170
00:56:46.041 --> 00:56:46.416
It's like,

1171
00:56:46.900 --> 00:56:48.681
ask people if they're interested in speaking.

1172
00:56:48.838 --> 00:56:55.150
And we just providing like a little bit of support drove a huge.

1173
00:56:55.534 --> 00:57:02.001
Shift in the volume and demographics of the talks that were submitted.

1174
00:57:02.521 --> 00:57:03.724
And then, three years later,

1175
00:57:04.061 --> 00:57:05.021
like, 45%

1176
00:57:05.264 --> 00:57:06.606
of the speakers are women.

1177
00:57:07.286 --> 00:57:08.467
I forget what the number was,

1178
00:57:08.505 --> 00:57:10.849
but I think it was almost even with male speakers.

1179
00:57:11.396 --> 00:57:12.036
PyCon.

1180
00:57:13.818 --> 00:57:15.177
I had an old tweet about this,

1181
00:57:15.193 --> 00:57:16.193
so I just pulled this up.

1182
00:57:16.833 --> 00:57:17.068
It says,

1183
00:57:17.130 --> 00:57:18.708
Hello from your Pycon Diversity chair.

1184
00:57:19.099 --> 00:57:21.271
So the percentage of Pycon talks by women,

1185
00:57:21.396 --> 00:57:22.083
2011,

1186
00:57:22.085 --> 00:57:22.521
it was 1%.

1187
00:57:22.521 --> 00:57:23.943
2012,

1188
00:57:23.943 --> 00:57:25.005
it was 7%.

1189
00:57:25.110 --> 00:57:25.951
2013,

1190
00:57:26.110 --> 00:57:27.050
15%.

1191
00:57:27.092 --> 00:57:31.574
2014 and 2015,

1192
00:57:31.576 --> 00:57:32.175
33%.

1193
00:57:32.177 --> 00:57:32.777
And 2016,

1194
00:57:32.797 --> 00:57:33.079
40%.

1195
00:57:33.079 --> 00:57:34.501
Problems have solutions.

1196
00:57:34.679 --> 00:57:37.579
That was a very inspiring story to me also.

1197
00:57:38.023 --> 00:57:41.626
Something that was less inspiring to me was that at the language Summit,

1198
00:57:41.829 --> 00:57:44.235
there wasn't a single woman in the room.

1199
00:57:45.389 --> 00:57:49.992
And I don't believe we have a single female committer to Core Python.

1200
00:57:50.813 --> 00:57:55.157
There wasn't ever ill intent,

1201
00:57:55.438 --> 00:58:02.570
but unfortunately we fell into the trap of not doing enough. Diversity reach out to try to get more people to come in.

1202
00:58:03.148 --> 00:58:03.664
To be honest,

1203
00:58:03.681 --> 00:58:04.586
it was a lot of white men.

1204
00:58:05.101 --> 00:58:06.414
So Guido wanted to change that.

1205
00:58:06.976 --> 00:58:13.461
I want at least two female core Python devs in the next year.

1206
00:58:13.753 --> 00:58:16.817
And I will try to train them myself if that's what it takes.

1207
00:58:18.139 --> 00:58:18.958
So come talk to me.

1208
00:58:21.322 --> 00:58:25.947
I believe one of the first people who took up that call was Marietta.

1209
00:58:35.643 --> 00:58:40.735
Even though I've always been passionate about technology and programming,

1210
00:58:41.143 --> 00:58:42.518
I also felt it.

1211
00:58:42.885 --> 00:58:46.449
Wasn't a welcoming environment for women.

1212
00:58:47.248 --> 00:58:50.795
My schoolmates who took computer science are mostly men.

1213
00:58:51.257 --> 00:58:52.835
Most of the professors were men.

1214
00:58:53.155 --> 00:58:54.039
And at work,

1215
00:58:54.414 --> 00:58:56.242
most of my coworkers were men.

1216
00:58:56.382 --> 00:59:04.382
And I just didn't really have examples or role models of women being successful in tech industry.

1217
00:59:07.117 --> 00:59:09.820
One of my coworkers went to PyCon.

1218
00:59:10.257 --> 00:59:12.039
He saw that at that conference,

1219
00:59:12.242 --> 00:59:14.443
there is this community called BiLadies,

1220
00:59:16.226 --> 00:59:17.324
and I felt like

1221
00:59:18.668 --> 00:59:19.509
I want to meet them.

1222
00:59:33.121 --> 00:59:34.590
So in 2015,

1223
00:59:34.981 --> 00:59:37.387
that's when I decided I want to go to PyCon.

1224
00:59:38.806 --> 00:59:40.047
At this conference,

1225
00:59:40.208 --> 00:59:44.811
I get to see a lot of women speaking and presenting.

1226
00:59:45.713 --> 00:59:48.213
At my previous tech conference,

1227
00:59:48.378 --> 00:59:49.518
all the speakers were men,

1228
00:59:49.635 --> 00:59:51.034
all the keynote speakers were men,

1229
00:59:51.121 --> 00:59:53.018
so this was really different.

1230
00:59:55.815 --> 00:59:59.862
One of the keynote speakers at that same conference was Guido van Drassen.

1231
01:00:00.034 --> 01:00:00.206
Hello,

1232
01:00:00.331 --> 01:00:00.768
everybody.

1233
01:00:01.612 --> 01:00:02.597
Glad to see you all.

1234
01:00:02.925 --> 01:00:07.097
I want to meet and see the creator of Python programming language.

1235
01:00:07.237 --> 01:00:10.282
And I will try to train them myself if that's what it takes.

1236
01:00:10.442 --> 01:00:11.501
I heard this speech.

1237
01:00:11.802 --> 01:00:12.264
However,

1238
01:00:12.362 --> 01:00:13.123
at that time,

1239
01:00:13.423 --> 01:00:15.661
I just didn't think that it's something

1240
01:00:17.005 --> 01:00:17.489
I could do.

1241
01:00:18.364 --> 01:00:21.030
I wasn't even contributing to the Python community.

1242
01:00:21.208 --> 01:00:23.568
I didn't contribute to open source at all.

1243
01:00:24.818 --> 01:00:25.474
I just thought,

1244
01:00:25.989 --> 01:00:29.599
I'm sure they will find women next year.

1245
01:00:35.318 --> 01:00:36.059
The year after,

1246
01:00:36.139 --> 01:00:40.925
I went back to Pycon U.S. and Guido van Rossum gave another keynote.

1247
01:00:41.043 --> 01:00:43.925
We still don't have two female core developers.

1248
01:00:44.206 --> 01:00:45.143
I think at that time,

1249
01:00:45.190 --> 01:00:47.371
that's something really clicked on me.

1250
01:00:47.487 --> 01:00:50.753
Like, I realized that there's something within me that says,

1251
01:00:50.956 --> 01:00:52.050
if nobody's doing it,

1252
01:00:52.768 --> 01:00:53.362
I will do it.

1253
01:00:55.159 --> 01:00:55.784
I wrote to

1254
01:00:56.159 --> 01:00:59.393
Guido van Rossum and I asked him for help.

1255
01:01:00.456 --> 01:01:02.190
Somehow, I felt really scared.

1256
01:01:02.378 --> 01:01:04.112
I just didn't feel like.

1257
01:01:04.818 --> 01:01:08.442
I deserve mentorship from Guido van Rossum.

1258
01:01:08.561 --> 01:01:12.626
So I was really hesitated to send this email to him.

1259
01:01:13.030 --> 01:01:13.724
But in the end,

1260
01:01:14.130 --> 01:01:14.905
I realized that

1261
01:01:15.311 --> 01:01:16.068
I want to try.

1262
01:01:16.170 --> 01:01:16.326
Like,

1263
01:01:16.364 --> 01:01:19.170
I felt like this was a great opportunity for me.

1264
01:01:19.489 --> 01:01:20.436
I pressed the send button.

1265
01:01:27.414 --> 01:01:28.335
I got a reply.

1266
01:01:28.855 --> 01:01:30.137
He was very friendly.

1267
01:01:30.518 --> 01:01:32.900
He started sharing resources about,

1268
01:01:32.920 --> 01:01:33.157
you know,

1269
01:01:33.239 --> 01:01:35.661
how to get started contributing to Python.

1270
01:01:36.021 --> 01:01:38.123
He offered to do like video chats.

1271
01:01:38.403 --> 01:01:41.489
It's been really helpful to have his moral support.

1272
01:01:41.889 --> 01:01:45.911
We had a pretty sort of deep mentorship relationship for a few years.

1273
01:01:46.927 --> 01:01:51.396
Mary learned the process from Guido and continued to contribute more and more,

1274
01:01:51.536 --> 01:01:52.443
very much around tooling.

1275
01:01:52.552 --> 01:01:55.036
Like, she really found her niche.

1276
01:01:55.525 --> 01:01:57.487
In terms of trying to help make our development process easier?

1277
01:01:58.548 --> 01:02:00.311
It was scary at first.

1278
01:02:00.349 --> 01:02:00.490
Like,

1279
01:02:00.530 --> 01:02:05.213
I just didn't feel comfortable sharing my questions in public.

1280
01:02:05.753 --> 01:02:07.378
I didn't want people to know that,

1281
01:02:08.378 --> 01:02:10.923
I don't know how to do certain things.

1282
01:02:11.478 --> 01:02:15.025
I didn't want people to see that I'm actually not that good.

1283
01:02:16.025 --> 01:02:19.306
But this is how it works in open source.

1284
01:02:19.463 --> 01:02:24.806
And the community has always been kind and helped me with my...

1285
01:02:25.422 --> 01:02:29.807
Questions without saying that you're stupid.

1286
01:02:29.865 --> 01:02:30.065
Like,

1287
01:02:30.487 --> 01:02:32.947
I never felt like I was being judged.

1288
01:02:34.452 --> 01:02:38.990
I think it does start with

1289
01:02:40.233 --> 01:02:45.288
Guido. The fact that Guido was very active in bringing more voices.

1290
01:02:45.478 --> 01:02:49.222
Into Python absolutely made Python better and stronger.

1291
01:02:49.403 --> 01:02:53.349
Just the way the whole community works and what we stand for,

1292
01:02:53.989 --> 01:02:56.130
thanks to Guido's leadership,

1293
01:02:56.411 --> 01:02:59.208
is where I want to be.

1294
01:03:00.090 --> 01:03:01.458
And I think that's true for a lot of people.

1295
01:03:10.739 --> 01:03:11.786
About six,

1296
01:03:11.943 --> 01:03:12.739
seven months.

1297
01:03:13.106 --> 01:03:15.286
After I started reaching out to Guido,

1298
01:03:15.726 --> 01:03:19.146
I was recommended to become a Python core developer.

1299
01:03:20.586 --> 01:03:24.349
It really wasn't until four months ago that for the first time ever,

1300
01:03:26.911 --> 01:03:37.465
there's a woman who became a Python core developer and earned that commit privilege.

1301
01:03:38.137 --> 01:03:42.277
First woman ever to join our team and has continued to be there and participate.

