01:03:42.637 --> 01:03:46.800
Try to help us, and always a very good advocate, to try to improve our diversity.

1303
01:03:50.809 --> 01:03:51.965
Now that I've seen the camera,

1304
01:03:51.965 --> 01:03:52.231
let's...

1305
01:03:53.847 --> 01:03:56.550
My life really changed after that.

1306
01:03:57.472 --> 01:04:01.534
A lot of opportunities opened up just because I'm a Python Pro developer.

1307
01:04:08.275 --> 01:04:12.639
Marietta went on to give her own set of talks about how important mentorship is.

1308
01:04:13.438 --> 01:04:17.782
When you don't have role models who you can relate to,

1309
01:04:19.744 --> 01:04:23.603
you start believing that you cannot do it.

1310
01:04:25.744 --> 01:04:25.978
Thank you.

1311
01:04:25.978 --> 01:04:26.510
Hi everybody,

1312
01:04:27.275 --> 01:04:28.197
my name is Marietta.

1313
01:04:28.713 --> 01:04:29.416
I'm a PyLady.

1314
01:04:31.572 --> 01:04:33.306
I run pyladies Vancouver.

1315
01:04:34.400 --> 01:04:36.025
I also help with the PyLadiesCon.

1316
01:04:36.501 --> 01:04:37.163
Ten years ago,

1317
01:04:37.262 --> 01:04:41.246
I was also in this room in the Pyladies luncheon at Pycon, U.S. 2015.

1318
01:04:41.945 --> 01:04:44.507
It was a life-changing event for me.

1319
01:04:45.672 --> 01:04:50.735
It was at that event that I felt for the first time in my life as a developer,

1320
01:04:52.117 --> 01:04:58.327
I felt like I belong in tech. Because I see 100 women in the room with me.

1321
01:04:58.985 --> 01:05:03.735
I just want other women to have role models.

1322
01:05:04.797 --> 01:05:06.235
I hope I can help inspire.

1323
01:05:06.235 --> 01:05:08.601
Inspire them and help them,

1324
01:05:09.101 --> 01:05:11.882
these opportunities belong to you, too.

1325
01:05:12.565 --> 01:05:20.889
You're all the reason. I do this because I know there is still a lot to do. And I know together we can help each other and support each other.

1326
01:05:23.217 --> 01:05:23.873
Okay,

1327
01:05:23.875 --> 01:05:24.342
I think that's it.

1328
01:05:25.014 --> 01:05:26.170
Thank you so much everybody.

1329
01:05:29.264 --> 01:05:34.248
I have been so consistently impressed by

1330
01:05:35.210 --> 01:05:50.376
the Python community's ability to have respectful and real reflection and dialogue about how to steward itself and how to move it forward. In a way that I find so

1331
01:05:50.492 --> 01:05:54.469
inspiring and a vision of what is possible in other communities.

1332
01:05:54.501 --> 01:05:55.860
And I mean that really sincerely.

1333
01:06:06.750 --> 01:06:15.621
There were an ever-growing number of sort of scientific disciplines where all the code was written in Python,

1334
01:06:15.818 --> 01:06:18.802
or a lot of it was prototyped in Python. At least.

1335
01:06:19.320 --> 01:06:22.762
And then the next step was machine learning packages,

1336
01:06:23.505 --> 01:06:26.786
which started with Tensorflow and was later followed by

1337
01:06:27.228 --> 01:06:29.286
PyTorch. For a long time,

1338
01:06:29.309 --> 01:06:39.864
Python was seen sort of as a scripting language that you would just do small things that you need to automate, and not production-ready code.

1339
01:06:40.177 --> 01:06:42.114
And so it wasn't given a ton of attention.

1340
01:06:42.396 --> 01:06:48.255
And then now AIML has sort of changed things, where it is now a business driver.

1341
01:06:48.735 --> 01:06:53.641
Appeals to people who are not professional programmers,

1342
01:06:53.820 --> 01:06:57.023
but need software to do a task.

1343
01:06:57.523 --> 01:07:01.507
There are some other languages like R, you can do some interesting stuff in,

1344
01:07:01.664 --> 01:07:05.492
but Python is really it for AIML these days.

1345
01:07:05.929 --> 01:07:13.773
Python has probably, like centuries of engineering time that has gone into code in the ecosystem, specifically on those topics.

1346
01:07:13.775 --> 01:07:15.023
So if you're using Python,

1347
01:07:15.039 --> 01:07:17.882
you're able to instantly tap into those libraries.

1348
01:07:18.179 --> 01:07:19.641
Meta has PyTorch,

1349
01:07:19.782 --> 01:07:23.684
which has an amazing Python API in front-end people can interact with.

1350
01:07:24.067 --> 01:07:25.286
There's also SciPy,

1351
01:07:25.708 --> 01:07:26.226
NumPy,

1352
01:07:26.586 --> 01:07:26.907
Numba,

1353
01:07:27.164 --> 01:07:27.851
Pandas.

1354
01:07:27.969 --> 01:07:31.070
There's a whole suite of really extensive tools.

1355
01:07:31.836 --> 01:07:37.523
Trying to build a language and a language ecosystem that is amenable to all of that is non-trivial.

1356
01:07:37.836 --> 01:07:39.117
That actually took real design,

1357
01:07:39.320 --> 01:07:39.836
real thought,

1358
01:07:39.914 --> 01:07:44.398
and real ecosystem collective innovation over the course of decades.

1359
01:07:44.648 --> 01:07:46.726
The back-end of those tools are usually

1360
01:07:47.211 --> 01:07:47.320
C.

1361
01:07:47.903 --> 01:07:52.248
Or Fortran, or some other native language that's much faster,

1362
01:07:52.710 --> 01:07:58.378
but would be difficult for someone with an AI background to program in.

1363
01:08:00.416 --> 01:08:03.181
And it continues to be used for all that by all the

1364
01:08:03.925 --> 01:08:06.378
AI scientists developing models,

1365
01:08:06.425 --> 01:08:07.659
and people training the models,

1366
01:08:07.721 --> 01:08:08.909
people using the models.

1367
01:08:09.081 --> 01:08:13.690
And that brings yet another increment of growth to the Python community.

1368
01:08:21.503 --> 01:08:22.824
Python's a fantastic language,

1369
01:08:22.885 --> 01:08:24.006
even if you're not a scientist.

1370
01:08:24.105 --> 01:08:29.569
I just don't think it would have risen to the level of dramatic usage without the science. first,

1371
01:08:29.671 --> 01:08:30.335
data science,

1372
01:08:30.373 --> 01:08:31.115
machine learning story.

1373
01:08:31.475 --> 01:08:33.052
We had a massive impact in the world.

1374
01:08:33.694 --> 01:08:33.935
You know,

1375
01:08:33.936 --> 01:08:40.225
I think one testament to the future of Python is, if you prompt any of the LLMs to do code generation today,

1376
01:08:40.615 --> 01:08:41.740
if it's front end,

1377
01:08:41.787 --> 01:08:42.710
it's going to be Javascript

1378
01:08:43.287 --> 01:08:44.694
If it's back end data analysis,

1379
01:08:44.694 --> 01:08:45.475
it's going to be Python.

1380
01:08:47.475 --> 01:08:48.115
That's the future.

1381
01:08:48.725 --> 01:08:49.990
And Python is a part of that future.

1382
01:08:50.416 --> 01:08:50.997
Lucky me that

1383
01:08:51.457 --> 01:08:53.498
I chose that language and not a different one.

1384
01:08:58.720 --> 01:08:58.845
Hey,

1385
01:08:58.862 --> 01:08:59.104
Diego.

1386
01:08:59.845 --> 01:09:00.002
Oh,

1387
01:09:00.025 --> 01:09:00.206
hello,

1388
01:09:00.462 --> 01:09:01.385
Monty.

1389
01:09:01.386 --> 01:09:02.604
I hope you don't mind being filmed.

1390
01:09:03.306 --> 01:09:04.167
Yeah.

1391
01:09:04.189 --> 01:09:04.306
Ah,

1392
01:09:04.470 --> 01:09:04.893
okay.

1393
01:09:04.894 --> 01:09:05.854
He's not following me.

1394
01:09:06.212 --> 01:09:06.806
All right.

1395
01:09:06.807 --> 01:09:07.087
Yeah,

1396
01:09:07.448 --> 01:09:09.931
she's shooting some b-roll for the documentary,

1397
01:09:09.948 --> 01:09:10.292
I think.

1398
01:09:10.400 --> 01:09:10.542
Ah,

1399
01:09:10.650 --> 01:09:10.962
nice.

1400
01:09:11.119 --> 01:09:16.323
I first used Python in 1997, or something like that.

1401
01:09:17.104 --> 01:09:17.543
Wow,

1402
01:09:17.604 --> 01:09:19.783
that's really early days.

1403
01:09:21.123 --> 01:09:22.546
So it's got 30 frames of animation.

1404
01:09:22.846 --> 01:09:23.585
Oh,

1405
01:09:23.586 --> 01:09:23.905
wow.

1406
01:09:24.104 --> 01:09:25.867
I told everyone that he would hate getting the DSA,

1407
01:09:26.506 --> 01:09:27.467
but they did it anyway.

1408
01:09:28.585 --> 01:09:28.748
Sorry,

1409
01:09:28.765 --> 01:09:29.287
the DSA?

1410
01:09:29.467 --> 01:09:30.569
Distinguished Service Award.

1411
01:09:30.804 --> 01:09:34.210
I labeled him in the annual report as like a leader in the Python community once,

1412
01:09:34.211 --> 01:09:35.069
and he made me take it out.

1413
01:09:35.912 --> 01:09:36.725
Yeah,

1414
01:09:36.726 --> 01:09:37.335
you can see that.

1415
01:09:37.725 --> 01:09:38.554
But nevertheless,

1416
01:09:39.335 --> 01:09:41.444
he was on the steering council for five years,

1417
01:09:42.506 --> 01:09:43.367
and he was a leader.

1418
01:09:43.617 --> 01:09:46.304
I got a job from a Python conference back in 2017.

1419
01:09:46.916 --> 01:09:47.737
I grew up in India,

1420
01:09:47.777 --> 01:09:48.457
I moved to Germany,

1421
01:09:48.457 --> 01:09:49.158
it changed my life.

1422
01:09:49.618 --> 01:09:55.646
So I think Python changed a lot of things for me and I just wanted to say, thank you for making this language.

1423
01:09:55.764 --> 01:09:56.568
It's very sweet.

1424
01:09:56.646 --> 01:10:00.389
Do you mind if I take a picture with you?

1425
01:10:00.390 --> 01:10:01.271
Or that you don't like it?

1426
01:10:01.287 --> 01:10:02.068
I'm so sorry,

1427
01:10:02.208 --> 01:10:06.208
I really don't like it, and especially not in busy places.

1428
01:10:06.381 --> 01:10:06.614
Okay,

1429
01:10:06.693 --> 01:10:07.833
no problem.

1430
01:10:07.835 --> 01:10:08.225
I get it.

1431
01:10:08.256 --> 01:10:08.381
Okay,

1432
01:10:08.458 --> 01:10:10.225
find me in a dark alley and I'll do it.

1433
01:10:10.333 --> 01:10:14.943
Okay.

1434
01:10:16.764 --> 01:10:19.668
I always kind of looked at myself as the bass player of Python,

1435
01:10:19.729 --> 01:10:20.470
which is great.

1436
01:10:20.550 --> 01:10:20.811
You know,

1437
01:10:20.813 --> 01:10:21.690
you can do a lot,

1438
01:10:21.713 --> 01:10:22.573
you can have fun,

1439
01:10:23.073 --> 01:10:24.519
and the spotlight's not on you.

1440
01:10:24.596 --> 01:10:25.957
And I love that.

1441
01:10:26.002 --> 01:10:29.127
I can't imagine having that kind of spotlight on you.

1442
01:10:30.100 --> 01:10:31.381
For so many years.

1443
01:10:31.661 --> 01:10:32.724
I heard a story from an

1444
01:10:33.122 --> 01:10:43.012
Apple VP of engineering that Steve Jobs had turned down their hire of Guido because he said he has his own following. And we don't want to have that kind of distraction.

1445
01:10:49.099 --> 01:10:51.863
Python has always been a language that changed.

1446
01:10:52.283 --> 01:10:54.145
We've never been one of those languages. That says,

1447
01:10:54.386 --> 01:10:57.149
if you write code against this version of Python,

1448
01:10:57.288 --> 01:11:00.153
it will run forever with any new version of the language.

1449
01:11:00.395 --> 01:11:03.636
We just simply have never been those people.

1450
01:11:05.457 --> 01:11:09.292
A PEP is an acronym for Python enhancement Proposal.

1451
01:11:09.855 --> 01:11:15.824
That's a document that's written by someone who wants to make a significant change to Python.

1452
01:11:16.230 --> 01:11:16.605
Basically,

1453
01:11:16.667 --> 01:11:19.042
you're trying to convince people that this is a good idea.

1454
01:11:19.371 --> 01:11:21.511
It would be sent for discussion for a mailing list.

1455
01:11:22.148 --> 01:11:22.889
And then, eventually,

1456
01:11:23.229 --> 01:11:23.488
Guido,

1457
01:11:23.750 --> 01:11:24.871
as the BDFL,

1458
01:11:25.051 --> 01:11:26.511
the benevolent dictator for life,

1459
01:11:26.569 --> 01:11:29.215
would decide whether your change was going in or not.

1460
01:11:30.155 --> 01:11:41.226
But people always have worried that the next change is going to be the one that changes the feel of the language.

1461
01:11:41.726 --> 01:11:43.524
It won't fit my brain anymore,

1462
01:11:43.774 --> 01:11:46.132
or it won't be accessible anymore.

1463
01:11:46.649 --> 01:11:48.992
I've actually seen people storm out of rooms saying,

1464
01:11:49.319 --> 01:11:50.617
you're ruining this language.

1465
01:11:50.960 --> 01:11:52.021
Some people take it very,

1466
01:11:52.341 --> 01:11:53.524
very personally and seriously.

1467
01:11:54.063 --> 01:11:56.625
And the Walrus operator was no different.

1468
01:11:57.386 --> 01:11:57.625
Yeah,

1469
01:11:57.809 --> 01:11:58.367
so pep,

1470
01:11:58.469 --> 01:11:58.628
pep,

1471
01:11:58.688 --> 01:11:58.828
pep,

1472
01:11:58.828 --> 01:11:59.886
572.

1473
01:12:00.426 --> 01:12:02.653
I don't know who coined the term the walrus operator,

1474
01:12:02.667 --> 01:12:04.136
but if you kind of turn your head,

1475
01:12:04.192 --> 01:12:04.934
it looks like a little

1476
01:12:05.636 --> 01:12:06.176
Walrus.

1477
01:12:07.371 --> 01:12:10.886
It was a new feature that was proposed,

1478
01:12:11.184 --> 01:12:12.809
but it was also a syntax change.

1479
01:12:13.448 --> 01:12:15.917
The Walrus operator lets you do assignments,

1480
01:12:16.090 --> 01:12:20.605
meaning put values into variables in places that you previously could not.

1481
01:12:21.895 --> 01:12:24.096
That was probably the most contentious language change,

1482
01:12:24.458 --> 01:12:25.000
oddly enough,

1483
01:12:25.859 --> 01:12:27.280
because it's kind of a minor thing,

1484
01:12:27.363 --> 01:12:34.604
but there was so much feeling about whether that should be added or not that it created kind of a bit of a ruckus.

1485
01:12:35.011 --> 01:12:37.573
When I first saw the Walrus operator,

1486
01:12:37.877 --> 01:12:38.690
I didn't like it.

1487
01:12:39.065 --> 01:12:41.675
It kind of felt a little unpythonic to me.

1488
01:12:42.127 --> 01:12:43.409
But then I started to play with it.

1489
01:12:43.832 --> 01:12:47.877
There was a particular use case that I came up with in my own code that I was like,

1490
01:12:47.988 --> 01:12:48.096
oh,

1491
01:12:48.144 --> 01:12:48.738
you know what?

1492
01:12:49.221 --> 01:12:50.550
This is actually pretty cool.

1493
01:12:51.231 --> 01:12:52.533
And so then I was like,

1494
01:12:52.573 --> 01:12:52.733
well,

1495
01:12:53.014 --> 01:12:54.935
it's something that I won't use very often,

1496
01:12:54.956 --> 01:12:55.837
but when I need it,

1497
01:12:56.015 --> 01:12:57.657
it's really great to have.

1498
01:12:57.680 --> 01:12:58.501
And I turned,

1499
01:12:58.502 --> 01:12:58.661
you know,

1500
01:12:58.662 --> 01:13:00.899
180 degrees and became a fan of it.

1501
01:13:01.078 --> 01:13:02.219
But it was very disruptive.

1502
01:13:05.789 --> 01:13:09.251
Language features, and especially syntax, can be a double-edged sword.

1503
01:13:09.376 --> 01:13:11.438
So one person's succinct,

1504
01:13:11.532 --> 01:13:17.001
elegant code can be another person's unreadable puzzle or a fusticated mess.

1505
01:13:17.594 --> 01:13:19.563
They were very strongly voiced.

1506
01:13:20.243 --> 01:13:23.567
Predictions about how bad it would be for Python.

1507
01:13:23.988 --> 01:13:27.472
And then, just because Python was so much more popular at the time,

1508
01:13:27.570 --> 01:13:30.434
there are so many places where people talk about Python.

1509
01:13:30.472 --> 01:13:30.676
I mean,

1510
01:13:30.753 --> 01:13:31.113
Twitter,

1511
01:13:31.192 --> 01:13:31.472
you know,

1512
01:13:31.511 --> 01:13:32.059
at the time.

1513
01:13:33.636 --> 01:13:34.699
This is all happening in public,

1514
01:13:34.778 --> 01:13:34.996
right?

1515
01:13:35.059 --> 01:13:36.246
And everyone can kind of,

1516
01:13:36.528 --> 01:13:37.199
with low effort,

1517
01:13:37.261 --> 01:13:38.465
throw their head into the ring.

1518
01:13:38.824 --> 01:13:42.590
And not everyone is going to restrain themselves when they're doing it.

1519
01:13:45.923 --> 01:13:47.987
I started being more and more convinced that

1520
01:13:48.345 --> 01:13:50.869
PeP 572 was actually the right thing to do.

1521
01:13:52.268 --> 01:13:53.271
I was the BDFL,

1522
01:13:54.792 --> 01:13:56.175
and I accepted the PEP.

1523
01:13:58.979 --> 01:13:59.877
And the next morning,

1524
01:13:59.979 --> 01:14:00.542
I woke up,

1525
01:14:04.237 --> 01:14:04.595
and

1526
01:14:05.658 --> 01:14:11.564
I felt miserable because of all the attacks that had happened before.

1527
01:14:14.363 --> 01:14:15.684
I sat down at my computer,

1528
01:14:17.064 --> 01:14:18.923
wrote a short email,

1529
01:14:20.385 --> 01:14:21.564
and hit send,

1530
01:14:21.966 --> 01:14:24.608
wherein I announced that I resigned as BDFL.

1531
01:14:25.787 --> 01:14:28.725
And that had an incredible impact.

1532
01:14:30.247 --> 01:14:32.452
Nobody had expected I would resign,

1533
01:14:33.247 --> 01:14:36.389
and certainly not that I would rage quit over this issue,

1534
01:14:37.483 --> 01:14:38.935
which essentially it was.

1535
01:14:56.795 --> 01:14:57.774
Transfer of power.

1536
01:14:58.798 --> 01:15:00.720
Now that PEP 572 is done,

1537
01:15:00.818 --> 01:15:06.962
I don't ever want to have to fight so hard for a PeP. And find that so many people despise my decisions.

1538
01:15:07.947 --> 01:15:11.485
I would like to remove myself entirely from the decision process.

1539
01:15:11.845 --> 01:15:15.752
I'm basically giving myself a permanent vacation from being BDFL,

1540
01:15:16.377 --> 01:15:18.173
and you all will be on your own.

1541
01:15:18.752 --> 01:15:20.954
I am not going to appoint a successor.

1542
01:15:21.798 --> 01:15:23.095
So what are you all going to do?

1543
01:15:23.336 --> 01:15:29.802
Create a democracy, anarchy, a dictatorship federation. I'll still be here, but I'm

1544
01:15:29.859 --> 01:15:32.943
trying to let you all figure something out for yourselves.

1545
01:15:33.003 --> 01:15:35.465
I'm tired and I need a very long break.

1546
01:15:36.988 --> 01:15:37.367
That was it.

1547
01:15:40.211 --> 01:15:41.328
I haven't read that.

1548
01:15:41.375 --> 01:15:41.890
That was,

1549
01:15:42.492 --> 01:15:43.875
I thought, that was pretty well written.

1550
01:15:46.600 --> 01:15:48.538
I like to say he mic dropped his way out.

1551
01:15:48.539 --> 01:15:48.725
You know,

1552
01:15:48.726 --> 01:15:49.350
he just was like,

1553
01:15:49.351 --> 01:15:49.742
I'm out.

1554
01:15:49.867 --> 01:15:50.304
I'm done.

1555
01:15:50.319 --> 01:15:51.319
You guys figure it out.

1556
01:15:51.788 --> 01:15:54.898
So it was a complete and total shock to me.

1557
01:15:55.429 --> 01:15:56.225
Yeah.

1558
01:15:56.226 --> 01:15:58.319
I just felt really sad about it.

1559
01:15:58.684 --> 01:16:03.844
I wish he would have retired under better circumstances.

1560
01:16:04.945 --> 01:16:10.007
I felt I needed to take a step back to sort of recover myself.

1561
01:16:10.649 --> 01:16:12.844
I think a lot of people really felt for Guido,

1562
01:16:13.265 --> 01:16:13.664
you know,

1563
01:16:14.086 --> 01:16:15.726
that he could be pushed to that point.

1564
01:16:16.430 --> 01:16:16.711
Like,

1565
01:16:19.164 --> 01:16:27.149
maybe we let him down to allow the vitriol over this.

1566
01:16:28.688 --> 01:16:32.887
Change to Python to push somebody that we cared about to that point?

1567
01:16:35.708 --> 01:16:46.114
We all perceived that it was like a momentous occasion, or like a significant change. That you would put a mark in your timeline, in the history book, in the history of Python,

1568
01:16:46.208 --> 01:16:46.412
right?

1569
01:16:46.458 --> 01:16:51.693
Because it had been run on the ADFL model for its entire existence.

1570
01:16:51.694 --> 01:16:53.270
So there was a little bit of uncertainty,

1571
01:16:53.520 --> 01:16:53.708
like,

1572
01:16:53.989 --> 01:16:56.020
can this work at all without guidance of Guido?

1573
01:16:56.671 --> 01:16:57.613
Kind of a parent saying,

1574
01:16:57.632 --> 01:17:00.033
it's time for you to grow up and figure it out on your own.

1575
01:17:00.335 --> 01:17:02.096
I'm not going to solve this problem for you.

1576
01:17:05.502 --> 01:17:09.386
First order of business was deciding on how to decide.

1577
01:17:09.963 --> 01:17:12.831
And it turns out some people have very strong opinions on voting systems.

1578
01:17:13.252 --> 01:17:15.144
Programmers love arguing about voting methods.

1579
01:17:15.738 --> 01:17:16.752
I remember thinking,

1580
01:17:17.456 --> 01:17:18.846
this isn't going to work.

1581
01:17:19.033 --> 01:17:20.769
A lot of strong voices.

1582
01:17:21.127 --> 01:17:22.690
It's really difficult when you have...

1583
01:17:22.935 --> 01:17:34.024
Hundreds of core developers and thousands of people online, and millions of people in the community, and probably billions of dollars of software that run on Python.

1584
01:17:34.984 --> 01:17:38.430
You can't think about that because it definitely gets overwhelming.

1585
01:17:38.938 --> 01:17:40.516
I will fully admit it was stressful.

1586
01:17:41.078 --> 01:17:42.828
I had to go to an ear,

1587
01:17:42.876 --> 01:17:47.407
nose and throat specialist because I actually was starting to choke on my own throat from the stress.

1588
01:17:47.657 --> 01:17:52.359
It was not fun because if we couldn't decide on how we were going to decide...

1589
01:17:52.807 --> 01:17:53.448
Project was done.

1590
01:17:53.769 --> 01:17:57.891
We really approached it like the nerdy engineers we are.

1591
01:17:58.193 --> 01:17:59.454
In Python classic fashion,

1592
01:17:59.456 --> 01:18:00.474
we wrote a bunch of PAPs.

1593
01:18:00.978 --> 01:18:05.103
We didn't want to rush it because we knew we were going to have to live with this, potentially forever.

1594
01:18:05.743 --> 01:18:18.618
But we also realized the world was watching and did not like the idea of not knowing whether the thing was going to be around in a year or not. Because we couldn't stop bickering among ourselves about how to run ourselves.

1595
01:18:18.908 --> 01:18:20.449
People sponsored different kinds of models.

1596
01:18:20.470 --> 01:18:21.350
I think there was one which was like,

1597
01:18:21.451 --> 01:18:24.292
let's pick another BDFL, because that's what we feel comfortable with.

1598
01:18:24.515 --> 01:18:27.713
And then there was various kinds of committees and councils,

1599
01:18:28.238 --> 01:18:31.119
and we ended up settling on the five-person steering committee.

1600
01:18:31.402 --> 01:18:31.979
Good morning,

1601
01:18:32.019 --> 01:18:32.261
PyCon.

1602
01:18:32.261 --> 01:18:32.823
Cheers.

1603
01:18:33.519 --> 01:18:34.667
Thanks so much for joining us.

1604
01:18:36.182 --> 01:18:38.994
So, welcome to our panel with Python Steering Council.

1605
01:18:39.573 --> 01:18:40.604
Because there's five people,

1606
01:18:40.636 --> 01:18:41.823
you don't have the same problem,

1607
01:18:41.948 --> 01:18:47.369
like all the stress and responsibility of making these decisions falling on one person.

1608
01:18:47.823 --> 01:18:52.809
I actually felt that it made sense for me to be on that first steering council,

1609
01:18:53.070 --> 01:18:56.430
given that there was no longer feeling so burned out or attacked,

1610
01:18:56.890 --> 01:18:59.134
to provide some amount of continuity.

1611
01:18:59.578 --> 01:19:00.539
You know how this goes.

1612
01:19:00.578 --> 01:19:02.078
When your kid goes off to college,

1613
01:19:02.140 --> 01:19:03.907
some of you may have experience with that,

1614
01:19:04.282 --> 01:19:07.234
you're no longer directly involved in their lives,

1615
01:19:07.422 --> 01:19:07.720
maybe,

1616
01:19:07.938 --> 01:19:10.390
but you never stop worrying.

1617
01:19:11.188 --> 01:19:14.547
And that's how I feel about Python at the moment.

1618
01:19:14.595 --> 01:19:15.484
And that's why I...

1619
01:19:20.810 --> 01:19:23.993
Why I nominated myself for the steering committee and here I am.

1620
01:19:25.993 --> 01:19:34.328
There were elections for the second year steering council, and first I nominated myself and then withdrew because there were enough other strong candidates.

1621
01:19:34.969 --> 01:19:40.828
They didn't need me and I was happy to sort of let go of it.

1622
01:19:50.971 --> 01:20:00.278
The legitimacy that came from the replacement springing up from the community is essential to it being accepted.

1623
01:20:00.684 --> 01:20:02.105
It came from us,

1624
01:20:02.582 --> 01:20:04.622
so it's accepted by us.

1625
01:20:05.349 --> 01:20:06.067
It works.

1626
01:20:06.224 --> 01:20:07.716
I think it works for us now.

1627
01:20:08.434 --> 01:20:12.309
There may be a time in the future where it doesn't work, or pieces of it don't work.

1628
01:20:13.012 --> 01:20:14.809
You have to be willing to evolve.

1629
01:20:15.155 --> 01:20:18.282
Change is the one universal constant of the universe.

1630
01:20:18.283 --> 01:20:24.809
And so things always change and you have to be ready and willing to adapt to change.

1631
01:20:38.640 --> 01:20:40.721
It started out as a hobby project,

1632
01:20:40.784 --> 01:20:41.363
definitely.

1633
01:20:41.604 --> 01:20:45.582
I think I probably wanted to prove something to myself more than anything.

1634
01:20:46.104 --> 01:20:49.519
It exceeded my wildest expectations,

1635
01:20:49.565 --> 01:20:51.565
and it actually continues to do so.

1636
01:20:53.721 --> 01:20:59.019
I constantly hear from people whose lives were completely changed by Python.

1637
01:20:59.895 --> 01:21:03.118
And it has created this incredible community,

1638
01:21:03.458 --> 01:21:09.305
which was also a complete sort of bonus over everything else

1639
01:21:09.884 --> 01:21:11.047
I had anticipated.

1640
01:21:11.305 --> 01:21:21.377
This community that has like a massive conference every year and smaller conferences in every continent,

1641
01:21:21.658 --> 01:21:22.064
I think,

1642
01:21:22.095 --> 01:21:23.220
except Antarctica.

1643
01:21:24.814 --> 01:21:27.845
There was one of the Python conferences where there was...

1644
01:21:28.028 --> 01:21:30.751
A few thousand people in the audience.

1645
01:21:31.270 --> 01:21:33.032
I remember just looking around and going,

1646
01:21:33.813 --> 01:21:35.574
this is mind-blowing.

1647
01:21:36.355 --> 01:21:37.676
That's the point at which

1648
01:21:38.536 --> 01:21:41.582
I knew we had achieved something important,

1649
01:21:42.520 --> 01:21:47.465
something that made a difference in people's lives and in the world.

1650
01:21:49.434 --> 01:21:54.653
Python turned out to be much more successful than perhaps any of us thought,

1651
01:21:54.715 --> 01:21:55.028
except...

1652
01:21:55.783 --> 01:21:57.005
Maybe Guido and his team,

1653
01:21:57.126 --> 01:21:59.688
I think they always believed that this was the future.

1654
01:21:59.726 --> 01:22:00.207
And, of course,

1655
01:22:00.247 --> 01:22:02.109
it's now one of the most popular,

1656
01:22:02.328 --> 01:22:05.212
if not the most popular programming language in the world.

1657
01:22:05.453 --> 01:22:10.320
He spent two weeks in Christmas in Like 1989, writing a programming language because he thought it would be fun.

1658
01:22:10.399 --> 01:22:16.890
Like, who would have imagined that that would be such a life-altering and also world-altering thing to have done?

1659
01:22:17.345 --> 01:22:19.984
I think it's been great for the world.

1660
01:22:20.109 --> 01:22:24.188
I think it's made people feel like they can get into programming.

1661
01:22:24.435 --> 01:22:25.655
When they never thought they could.

1662
01:22:25.837 --> 01:22:28.078
I think it made programming accessible to people.

1663
01:22:28.354 --> 01:22:42.284
It's literally part of kindergarten through grade 12 education around the world. And is on Mars. Thanks to being used as a scripting language to process the parachute at the Perseverance Rover landing.

1664
01:22:42.471 --> 01:22:45.738
Like, it's hard to think of anything that hasn't been touched by some Python code somewhere.

1665
01:22:45.988 --> 01:22:47.082
It's mind-boggling.

1666
01:22:47.738 --> 01:22:48.925
It's an important language.

1667
01:22:49.488 --> 01:22:52.409
It's a popular language, that's a vibrant and

1668
01:22:52.804 --> 01:23:07.775
relevant language today, as much as it was in the past, and I believe as much as it will be in the future. Programmers 30 years from now will be like, Oh yeah, you know, I'm still using Python. Just like today, people are still using Fortran and C and

1669
01:23:07.777 --> 01:23:16.306
C plus plus. And those are old languages, you know, too, in the scheme of thing scheme list, another old language. So, yeah,

1670
01:23:40.560 --> 01:23:40.670
now

1671
01:23:40.685 --> 01:23:42.295
I keep thinking of, like, weird jokes.

1672
01:23:42.608 --> 01:23:44.795
There's this library in Python called pickles,

1673
01:23:45.764 --> 01:23:48.014
because pickle is a funny word,

1674
01:23:48.060 --> 01:23:48.372
I guess.

1675
01:23:48.983 --> 01:23:51.435
The documentation used to have a footnote about

1676
01:23:51.652 --> 01:23:53.359
how you should imagine Guido and

1677
01:23:53.801 --> 01:23:55.609
Jim sniffing pickles.
